be the best available statement of a distinctive philosophical position – the assertion of a moral self reliance – which is found throughout American literature … a peculiar strain of cussedness which seems to me to be an essential property of the American mind.’ That ‘strain of cussedness’ is explored in various ways in this book. These are essays which provoke and advance scholarship and critical insight. Strict philosophical rigour is sometimes ‘strained’ in favour of unity, but the essays, in their juxtaposition, suggest that the stoic theme in American literature is a fruitful subject for exploration. The book contains essays and tributes by Peter Buitenhuis, Milton R. Stern, Gay Wilson Allen, Munro Beattie, Richard Allan Davison, Roger B. Salomon, Melvin K. Backman, Daniel Fuchs, Lewis A. Lawson, Tom Middlebro, George Johnston, and the editor, Duane J. MacMillan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aAuthors, Americany20th centuryvBiography. 0aStoics in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Gay Wilson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBackman, Melvin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeattie, Munro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuitenhuis, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavison, Richard Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawson, Lewis A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacMillan, Duane J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary